SOLUTION:

üîí Day 2 Lab: Creating an AWS Security Group
üìñ Lab Explanation
Today, we're creating a Security Group - essentially a virtual firewall that controls inbound and outbound traffic for your AWS resources. This is crucial for securing your cloud infrastructure.

üîç Key Terms Defined
Security Group
What: A virtual firewall that controls traffic to AWS resources

Purpose: Defines which network traffic is allowed to reach your instances

Stateful: If you allow inbound traffic, the response is automatically allowed outbound

VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)
What: Your own isolated virtual network in AWS

Default VPC: Automatically created in each AWS region for your account

CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing)
What: A method for allocating IP addresses

0.0.0.0/0: Represents all IP addresses (anywhere on the internet)

Inbound Rules
What: Rules controlling incoming traffic to your resources

Examples: HTTP (port 80), SSH (port 22), HTTPS (port 443)

üöÄ Benefits & Why We Use Security Groups
üîí Security Advantages
Instance-Level Firewall - protects individual resources

Flexible Rules - easily modify as your needs change

Default Deny - all traffic is blocked unless explicitly allowed

üí° Practical Benefits
Easy Management - apply same rules to multiple instances

Dynamic - can modify rules without restarting instances

Cost-Effective - no additional cost for security groups

üéØ Use Cases
Web Servers - allow HTTP/HTTPS traffic from internet

Application Servers - restrict access to specific sources

Database Servers - allow access only from application servers

Bastion Hosts - allow SSH access from specific IP ranges

üõ†Ô∏è Step-by-Step Solution
Method: AWS Management Console
Login to AWS Console

bash
# Use the provided credentials:
URL: https://651872811359.signin.aws.amazon.com/console?region=us-east-1
Username: kk_labs_user_631354
Password: QM^hd@@8qIu^
Region: us-east-1 (VERIFY THIS!)
Navigate to VPC/EC2 Service

Go to Services ‚Üí VPC or EC2

In left sidebar, find "Security" ‚Üí "Security Groups"

Create Security Group

Click "Create security group"

Basic details:

Security group name: devops-sg

Description: Security group for Nautilus App Servers

VPC: Select default VPC

Configure Inbound Rules

Rule 1 - HTTP:

Type: HTTP

Port range: 80

Source: 0.0.0.0/0

Rule 2 - SSH:

Type: SSH

Port range: 22

Source: 0.0.0.0/0

Click "Add rule" for each

Outbound Rules (Leave as default)

Default allows all outbound traffic

Create Security Group

Click "Create security group"

Verify creation in the security groups list

üìã What We Created
Name: devops-sg

Description: Security group for Nautilus App Servers

Inbound Rules:

HTTP (port 80) from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0)

SSH (port 22) from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0)

‚ö†Ô∏è Security Notes
0.0.0.0/0 allows access from ANY IP address

In production, restrict SSH access to specific IP ranges

Consider adding HTTPS (port 443) for secure web traffic

